Critiques of AI generated Test Cases -

AUTH/PROF/SAVE - These test cases are reasonable approaches to browser behavior. A session stored in cookies, invalid credentials hadnled, a database reference, a redirect. This handles a flow and seems complete. What
it lacks however is any complete understanding of what will do all of this. Is the website solely browser based? Does it function locally or is it hosted on a web server? This would require extensive additional work
to flesh out what are honestly good test cases. I think these are all usable and some will generate additional sub cases to explore. None are overly specific at this point, which is good.

I would add more regarding what is used for a user profile (email or other login integration) and how to handle security beyond just redirect to login. Such as what conditions cause this and what options are experienced.

SAVE cases are a mix of how to manage a save, what it attaches to (a profile) and if this save action has edge cases such as if it is sudden or mid-game versus at a known point like file creation. 

I would add situations related to abandoned play sessions (like auto save) or if these data integrity or conflict checks actually are describing a situation I want to encourage? Maybe only one active play session per user
is going to be allowed. This would change a conflict test flow and needs to be worked more fully to redirect the AI using new constraints.


MOVE - These are more interesting as the AI is trying to imagine more than I would expect to decide at this point. Yes we should check to see that a character can move, yes there would be velocity and boundary checks to 
define the movement is appropriate and recoverable if unintended action occurs. It wants to literally jump ahead and imagine a Z access. This would expand velocity to a 3-D realistic setting involving "gravity" or other natural limitations.
Overall this is a very complete approach from the AI and I believe this is because the topic is so clearly self-defined. Its been done before the same way and thats what AI is best used to generate quickly.

It wants to define movement in all directions, how to check the speed, how to define boundaries and avoid game breaking area conflicts. Thats actually nearly all I would imagine to check on this topic! I would certainly remove nothing. 

I would want to add object boundaries and static mesh situations as this is how movement will overlap with a real enviornment. The language used by the AI in the test outcomes indicates awareness of these topics.

It did not describe anything related to object interactions so that is the next thing which should be handled. It would require defining what gameplay elements might appear so it will require more permanent decisions.

